SENATE BILL 513
E4 6lr1592
CF HB 149
By: Senator Smith
Introduced and read first time: February 2, 2026
Assigned to: Education, Energy, and the Environment
Committee Report: Favorable with amendments
Senate action: Adopted
Read second time: March 20, 2026
CHAPTER ______
1 AN ACT concerning
2 Fire Prevention – Assistant Fire Marshals, Residential Rental High–Rise
3 Property Fire Safety Equipment, and Fire Alarm System Technicians
4 FOR the purpose of authorizing a county or municipal corporation to designate certain fire
5 marshals with the approval of the State Fire Marshal or to request that the State
6 Fire Marshal designate certain fire marshals and requiring the State Fire Marshal
7 to adopt certain regulations governing the qualifications, training, standards, and
8 certification of designees; requiring installation of certain fire prevention in certain
9 high–rise residential buildings; requiring the State Fire Prevention Commission to
10 adopt certain regulations relating to fire alarm system technicians; and generally
11 relating to fire safety.
12 BY repealing and reenacting, with amendments,
13 Article – Public Safety
14 Section 6–304, 9–102, 9–901, and 9–902
15 Annotated Code of Maryland
16 (2022 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
17 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
18 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
19 Article – Public Safety
20 6–304.
EXPLANATION: CAPITALS INDICATE MATTER ADDED TO EXISTING LAW.
[Brackets] indicate matter deleted from existing law.
Underlining indicates amendments to bill.
Strike out indicates matter stricken from the bill by amendment or deleted from the law by
amendment. *sb0513*

2 SENATE BILL 513
1 (a) (1) A county or municipal corporation of the State may designate WITH
2 THE APPROVAL OF THE STATE FIRE MARSHAL, OR MAY REQUEST THAT THE STATE
3 FIRE MARSHAL DESIGNATE, a fire marshal or appropriate fire official to serve as
4 assistant State fire marshal to carry out this title, including issuing orders, in that county
5 or municipal corporation.
6 (2) An assistant State fire marshal may not receive compensation from the
7 State.
8 (3) The State Fire Marshal shall carry out this title in a county or
9 municipal corporation that [has not] DOES NOT HAVE A designated [an] assistant State
10 fire marshal.
11 (b) (1) [An assistant State fire marshal shall have at least completed National
12 Fire Protection Association (NFPA) Standard 1031 – Fire Inspector I, or the equivalent, as
13 determined by the State Fire Marshal.] THE STATE FIRE MARSHAL SHALL ADOPT
14 REGULATIONS ESTABLISHING REQUIREMENTS FOR ALL INDIVIDUALS DESIGNATED
15 AS AN ASSISTANT STATE FIRE MARSHAL OR A SPECIAL ASSISTANT STATE FIRE
16 MARSHAL UNDER SUBSECTION (A)(1) OF THIS SECTION, INCLUDING:
17 (I) MINIMUM TRAINING, CERTIFICATION, AND OTHER
18 STANDARDS RELATING TO FIRE INSPECTION;
19 (II) MINIMUM TRAINING, CERTIFICATION, AND OTHER
20 STANDARDS FOR FIRE PLAN REVIEW, A FIRE PLAN EXAMINER, OR FIRE PLAN
21 ENGINEERING STAFF;
22 (III) MINIMUM TRAINING, CERTIFICATION, AND OTHER
23 STANDARDS RELATING TO FIRE INSPECTION INVESTIGATION;
24 (IV) ACCEPTABLE MINIMUM STANDARDS FOR THE ELIGIBILITY
25 OF AN INDIVIDUAL TO SERVE AS AN ASSISTANT STATE FIRE MARSHAL OR A SPECIAL
26 ASSISTANT STATE FIRE MARSHAL; AND
27 (V) POLICIES FOR APPLICATION FOR, REVIEW OF, EXPIRATION
28 OF, RENEWAL OF, AND PROBATIONARY STATUS FOR THE POSITIONS OF ASSISTANT
29 STATE FIRE MARSHAL AND SPECIAL ASSISTANT STATE FIRE MARSHAL.
30 (2) The State Fire Marshal may administer an examination based on
31 NFPA [Standard 1031] STANDARDS AS RELEVANT FOR THE REQUIREMENTS LISTED
32 IN PARAGRAPH (1) OF THIS SUBSECTION before designating an individual as an
33 assistant State fire marshal OR SPECIAL ASSISTANT STATE FIRE MARSHAL.

SENATE BILL 513 3
1 (c) (1) The State Fire Marshal may designate as a special assistant State fire
2 marshal:
3 (i) a law enforcement officer involved in arson investigations;
4 (ii) any other suitable individual who meets the standards
5 established under this section; or
6 (iii) on the advice of an assistant State fire marshal, a member of a
7 fire department if:
8 1. the designee is a full–time employee of the fire
9 department;
10 2. the designee performs fire inspections or fire
11 investigations for the fire department; and
12 3. the fire department is organized and operates in the State.
13 (2) A special assistant State fire marshal serves at the pleasure of the State
14 Fire Marshal.
15 (3) A special assistant State fire marshal may not receive compensation
16 from the State.
17 (4) Each special assistant State fire marshal shall assist the State Fire
18 Marshal in carrying out the duties of the State Fire Marshal under this title.
19 (d) The Commission may remove an assistant or special assistant State fire
20 marshal for just cause by a majority decision:
21 (1) on the recommendation of the State Fire Marshal; and
22 (2) after an administrative hearing.
23 9–102.
24 (a) (1) In this section, “high–rise building” means a building [for human
25 occupancy that is:
26 (i) seven or more stories above grade level; or
27 (ii) over 75 feet in height] WHERE THE FLOOR OF AN OCCUPIABLE
28 STORY IS GREATER THAN 75 FEET ABOVE THE LOWEST LEVEL OF FIRE DEPARTMENT
29 VEHICLE ACCESS.
30 (2) “High–rise building” does not include:

4 SENATE BILL 513
1 (i) a structure or building used exclusively for open–air parking; or
2 (ii) a building used exclusively for agricultural purposes.
3 (b) This subtitle applies throughout the State, including Baltimore City.
4 (c) (1) An automatic smoke alarm shall be provided in each sleeping area
5 within each residential occupancy, including one– and two–family dwellings, lodging or
6 rooming houses, hotels, dormitories, and apartment buildings, as defined in NFPA 101: Life
7 Safety Code as adopted by the State Fire Prevention Commission.
8 (2) (i) Beginning July 31, 2025, smoke detectors shall be installed in
9 accordance with location and spacing requirements established by the National Fire
10 Protection Association in each interior public corridor in a residential rental high–rise
11 building.
12 (ii) A county may not require upgrades to fire safety systems not
13 specified in subparagraph (i) of this paragraph as a condition of issuing a permit for the
14 installation of smoke detectors required under subparagraph (i) of this paragraph.
15 (3) (I) IN THIS PARAGRAPH, “SUBSTANTIAL RENOVATION” MEANS
16 PERMANENT ALTERATIONS THAT:
17 1. ARE INTENDED TO ENHANCE THE VALUE OF A
18 BUILDING; AND
19 2. COST AN AMOUNT EQUAL TO OR GREATER THAN 40%
20 OF THE VALUE OF THE BUILDING AS ASSESSED BY THE STATE DEPARTMENT OF
21 ASSESSMENTS AND TAXATION.; AND
22 3. MEET THE CRITERIA FOR SUBSTANTIAL RENOVATION
23 UNDER ANY APPLICABLE LOCAL LAW.
24 (II) BEGINNING OCTOBER 1, 2026, AUTOMATIC FIRE
25 SPRINKLERS SHALL BE INSTALLED IN ACCORDANCE WITH NFPA LIFE SAFETY
26 CODE AND NFPA STANDARDS IN EACH RESIDENTIAL RENTAL HIGH–RISE BUILDING
27 THAT IS UNDERGOING A SUBSTANTIAL RENOVATION THAT RECEIVES BUILDING
28 PERMITS ON OR AFTER OCTOBER 1, 2026.
29 (III) IN DETERMINING WHETHER A PROPOSED SUBSTANTIAL
30 RENOVATION IS INTENDED TO ENHANCE THE VALUE OF A BUILDING EXCLUSIVE OF
31 LAND VALUE, A COUNTY MAY CONSIDER BUILDING IMPROVEMENTS COMPLETED
32 OVER A 4–YEAR TIME PERIOD FROM THE DATE OF THE INITIAL BUILDING PERMIT.:

SENATE BILL 513 5
1 1. THE EXISTING PHYSICAL CONDITION OF THE RENTAL
2 HOUSING;
3 2. WHETHER THE EXISTING PHYSICAL CONDITION
4 IMPAIRS OR TENDS TO IMPAIR THE HEALTH, SAFETY, AND SECURITY OF ANY
5 TENANT;
6 3. WHETHER THE DEFICIENCIES IN THE EXISTING
7 PHYSICAL CONDITIONS COULD INSTEAD BE CORRECTED BY IMPROVED
8 MAINTENANCE OR REPAIR; AND
9 4. WHETHER THE PROPOSED RENOVATIONS ARE
10 OPTIONAL OR COSMETIC CHANGES.
11 (IV) A SUBSTANTIALLY RENOVATED RESIDENTIAL RENTAL
12 HIGH–RISE BUILDING SHALL ALSO HAVE THE FOLLOWING FIRE PROTECTION AND
13 LIFE SAFETY FEATURES:
14 1. SMOKE ALARMS OR HEAT DETECTORS IN EVERY
15 SLEEPING AREA;
16 2. STAIRWELLS ENCLOSED WITH AT LEAST 2–HOUR FIRE
17 RESISTANCE RATED CONSTRUCTION WITH AT LEAST 90–MINUTE FIRE RESISTANCE
18 RELATED RATED, SELF–CLOSING, AND SELF–LATCHING DOORS;
19 3. AT LEAST 20–MINUTE FIRE RESISTANCE RATED
20 CORRIDOR DOORS UNLESS PARTIAL SPRINKLER PROTECTION IS PROVIDED WITH
21 APPROPRIATELY RATED CORRIDOR WALLS;
22 4. SMOKEPROOF EXIT ENCLOSURES VIA NATURAL
23 VENTILATION, MECHANICAL VENTILATION INCORPORATING A VESTIBULE, OR
24 PRESSURIZING THE STAIR ENCLOSURE;
25 5. AT LEAST TWO SMOKE COMPARTMENTS ON EACH
26 FLOOR; AND
27 6. DECREASED MAXIMUM EXIT ACCESS TRAVEL
28 DISTANCES INADEQUATE FIRE PUMPS REPLACED WHEN NECESSARY.
29 (d) Smoke alarms shall:
30 (1) be installed in accordance with NFPA 72: National Fire Alarm and
31 Signaling Code as referenced by the State Fire Prevention Code;

6 SENATE BILL 513
1 (2) be listed and labeled by a nationally recognized testing laboratory to
2 comply with Underwriters Laboratories (UL) 217, “Standard for safety for single and
3 multiple station smoke alarms”;
4 (3) be suitable for sensing visible or invisible products of combustion; and
5 (4) sound an alarm suitable to warn the occupants.
6 (e) Local jurisdictions may adopt smoke alarm regulations that are more
7 stringent than the provisions of this subtitle.
8 9–901.
9 (A) In this subtitle[, “fire] THE FOLLOWING WORDS HAVE THE MEANINGS
10 INDICATED.
11 (B) “FIRE ALARM SYSTEM TECHNICIAN” MEANS A PERSON WHO IS ENGAGED
12 IN THE PERFORMANCE, INSTALLATION, DOCUMENTATION, PLANNING, AND
13 COORDINATION OF THE PERIODIC INSPECTION AND TESTING OF EXISTING FIRE
14 ALARM SYSTEMS AND THEIR COMPONENTS, NOT INCLUDING THE COMMISSIONING
15 OF NEW SYSTEMS.
16 (C) “FIRE sprinkler contractor” means a person who designs, installs, inspects,
17 tests, repairs, or modifies a fire sprinkler system.
18 9–902.
19 (a) (1) The State Fire Prevention Commission shall adopt regulations to
20 establish a program to license and regulate fire sprinkler contractors in the State.
21 [(b)] (2) The State Fire Prevention Commission shall adopt regulations to:
22 [(1)] (I) define fire sprinkler contractor;
23 [(2)] (II) define fire sprinkler system[,] in a manner that does not conflict
24 with § 12–101(l), (m), or (n) of the Business Occupations and Professions Article;
25 [(3)] (III) designate and identify exemptions to the regulations;
26 [(4)] (IV) establish requirements for licensure including professional and
27 technical standards and requirements for liability insurance;
28 [(5)] (V) establish a schedule of fees for licenses that will recover but not
29 exceed the direct and indirect costs associated with the issuance of the licenses; and

SENATE BILL 513 7
1 [(6)] (VI) establish procedures for the State Fire Marshal to deny, suspend,
2 or revoke the license of a person who fails to comply with any regulation adopted by the
3 State Fire Prevention Commission under this subtitle.
4 (B) (1) THE STATE FIRE PREVENTION COMMISSION SHALL ADOPT
5 REGULATIONS TO ESTABLISH A PROGRAM TO LICENSE AND REGULATE FIRE ALARM
6 SYSTEM TECHNICIANS AND FIRE ALARM SYSTEM COMPANIES IN THE STATE.
7 (2) THE STATE FIRE PREVENTION COMMISSION SHALL ADOPT
8 REGULATIONS TO:
9 (I) DEFINE FIRE ALARM SYSTEM TECHNICIAN;
10 (II) DEFINE FIRE ALARM SYSTEM IN A MANNER THAT DOES NOT
11 CONFLICT WITH § 12–101(L), (M), OR (N) OF THE BUSINESS OCCUPATIONS AND
12 PROFESSIONS ARTICLE;
13 (III) DESIGNATE AND IDENTIFY EXEMPTIONS TO THE
14 REGULATIONS;
15 (IV) ESTABLISH REQUIREMENTS FOR LICENSURE, INCLUDING
16 PROFESSIONAL AND TECHNICAL STANDARDS AND REQUIREMENTS FOR LIABILITY
17 INSURANCE;
18 (V) ESTABLISH A SCHEDULE OF FEES FOR LICENSES THAT WILL
19 RECOVER BUT NOT EXCEED THE DIRECT AND INDIRECT COSTS ASSOCIATED WITH
20 THE ISSUANCE OF THE LICENSES; AND
21 (VI) ESTABLISH PROCEDURES FOR THE STATE FIRE MARSHAL
22 TO DENY, SUSPEND, OR REVOKE THE LICENSE OF A PERSON WHO FAILS TO COMPLY
23 WITH ANY REGULATION ADOPTED BY THE STATE FIRE PREVENTION COMMISSION
24 UNDER THIS SUBTITLE.
25 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
26 October 1, 2026.

